Acute effect workshop time series analysis example

Chen Chen

21 October, 2022

Here I am showing an example of time-series analysis looking at the acute effect of daily average fine particulate matter (\(PM_{2.5}\)) on incident rate of daily cardiovascular hospitalization among those age 65 and up in 192 California ZIP-Code Tabulation Areas (ZCTA) from 2006 to 2013. In this example, daily temperature and daily dew point temperature are considered as potential confounders.

library(knitr) ## for Rmarkdonw functions
library(data.table) ## for easy handling of data
library(splines) ## for "ns" function
# remotes::install_github("rdpeng/tlnise") ## installation of tlnise package. There are other packages that conducts Bayesian hierarchical model as well (R2OpenBUGS).
library(tlnise) ## for Bayesian hierarchical model pooling
library(mvmeta) ## for random-effect meta-regression pooling
library(ggplot2) ## for plotting

Quick look at the data (one ZCTA)

Due to privacy concern, I could not show the real data but here is a fake example from one random ZCTA. Daily temperature and daily dew point temperature are potential time-varying confounders for \(PM_{2.5}\)~cardiovascular hospitalization relationship.

date: corresponding date of the row.
zcta: ZIP-Code Tabulation Areas for the data. Forced to be 66666 for privacy concern.
pop: annual average population 65 and older in ZCTA 66666.
cardio_disease: number of cardiovascular disease hospitalizations among those 65 and older in ZCTA 66666. Forced to be 0 for privacy concern.
mean_pm25: daily average \(PM_{2.5}\) concentration (\(\mu g/m^3\)) in ZCTA 66666.
tmpt: daily average temperature (Celsius degree) in ZCTA 66666.
dptp: daily average dew point temperature (Celsius degree) in ZCTA 66666.

Cleaning of dataset and add necessary variables

Here I added rolling average of previous three-day temperature and dew point temperature to account for confounding from meteorological conditions from previous few days. I also included day of week to account for differences in hospitalization and \(PM_{2.5}\) across weekdays.

## create new time variable & day of week
dt <- dt[order(dt$date), ]
dt$day <- seq(1:length(unique(dt$date)))
dt$dow <- as.factor(format(dt$date, "%w")) #reference category is Sunday

## create moving average of previous three-day temperature/dew point temperature
dt[, rmtmpt:= shift(frollapply(dt$tmpt, n=3, FUN=mean, fill=NA, align="right"), n = 1, fill = NA, type = "lag")]
dt[, rmdptp := shift(frollapply(dt$dptp, n=3, FUN=mean, fill=NA, align="right"), n = 1, fill = NA, type = "lag")]

Last, I evaluated data missing in the dataset since only rows with complete data will be included in the model and I dont want any pattern in the data missing. The data missing in this dataset is minimal and seems to be related to \(PM_{2.5}\) dataset only so we will ignore them.

Choose the geographical units (ZCTAs) to include in the study

I stated in the begininig that I included 192 ZCTAs in this study but how did I reach this number? Why not include all ZCTAs?
Since we need to estimate many parameters in our model, it is important to only include geographical units with large enough populations to avoid extensive zeros in the data that might 1) lead to low statistical power to detect any effect; 2) violate the independent outcome assumption in quasi-Poisson model, lead to failure to converge and requires application of zero-inflated quasi-Poisson model.
In this study I established the criteria for selecting ZCTAs: 1) with a census 2010 population larger than 50000; 2) with acceptable amount of data (50% of every day data) in each year of 2006-2013. Such criteria should be specified a prior.
Here is a map showing the study area (192 ZCTAs within California). Please ignore the colors.

Quasi-Poisson regression

Here I am showing the example code of running quasi-Poisson regression for one ZCTA. In the real study, I ran this for all 192 ZCTAs.

nyr <- 8 # number of years from 2006 to 2013
ndf <- 8 # number of degree of freedom per year in the spline function to account for long-term temporal trends, chosen based on previous knowledge, e.g., Dominici et al. 2006 and Peng et al. 2006
df.tp <- 3 # number of degree of freedom for temperature terms; normally this is 6 but Califronia has a narrower range of temperature
df.dp <- 3 # number of degree of freedom for dew point temperature terms

f <- glm(cardio_disease ~ offset(log(pop)) + mean_pm25 + ns(day, df = nyr * ndf) + ns(tmpt, df.tp) + ns(dptp, df.dp) + ns(rmtmpt, df.tp) + ns(rmdptp, df.dp), data=dt, family = quasipoisson)

Here is how the results would look like.

Results pooling

After conducting ZCTA specific analysis, we need to pool results across the geographical units to incorporate information from all locations to improve the precision of our estimates.
For the example study, we read in Poison regression results from all 192 ZCTAs to aggregate them across using both the tlnise package and the mvmeta package. The former employs a Bayesian hierarchical model with normal approximation of estimates from quasi-Poisson model. The latter employs meta regression with random intercept for each municipal. Results are similar between the two methods. Both method could incorporate consideration of effect modification (w in tlnise and add variables for formula in meta).

Here is how the ZCTA specific results look like:

print(head(foo))
##    ZCTA5          beta          se dispersion

Here is the pooling of results using two methods.

### meta-regression
out.m1 <- mvmeta(foo$beta, S = (foo$se)^2, method="reml")
temp <- c(exp(coef(out.m1)), exp(coef(out.m1) - 1.96*sqrt(vcov(out.m1))),  exp(coef(out.m1) + 1.96*sqrt(vcov(out.m1))))
names(temp) <- c("Estimation", "Lower limit for 95% CI", "Upper limit for 95% CI")
print(temp)
##             Estimation Lower limit for 95% CI Upper limit for 95% CI 
##               1.001750               1.000936               1.002564
## Bayesian hierarchical model--see details in Everson and Morris 2000
out <- tlnise(Y = foo$beta, V = (foo$se)^2, w = rep(1, nrow(foo)), seed=1234, maxiter = 5000, prnt = FALSE) ## I set w=1 for all ZCTAs, which could be replaced by community effect modifiers 
## Estimate and 95% CI of regional mean using posterior mean and SD for stage-two gamma
temp <- c(exp(out$gamma[, "est"]), exp(out$gamma[, "est"] - 1.96*out$gamma[, "se"]), exp(out$gamma[, "est"] + 1.96*out$gamma[, "se"]))
names(temp) <- c("Estimation", "Lower limit for 95% CI", "Upper limit for 95% CI")
print(temp)
##             Estimation Lower limit for 95% CI Upper limit for 95% CI 
##               1.001802               1.000935               1.002670
## below I estimated the 95% CI using random pulls from the posterior distribution
## this is useful when more complicated transformations are needed
gs <- tlnise:::sampleGamma(out, V = (foo$se)^2, Y = foo$beta) ## generate samples of gammastar, Dstar from equation (14) of Everson & Morris
sampsGamma <- tlnise:::drawSample0(gs, n=10000)
## Estimate and 95% CI of regional mean using random pulls from posterior distribution
temp <- c(exp(mean(sampsGamma)), exp(quantile(sampsGamma, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))))
names(temp) <- c("Estimation", "Lower limit for 95% CI", "Upper limit for 95% CI")
print(temp)
##             Estimation Lower limit for 95% CI Upper limit for 95% CI 
##               1.001797               1.000917               1.002690

Sensitivity analysis

When we are only interested in one ZCTA, we could conduct sensitivity analyses as below. However, most of the time (including in the example study), we are interested in a pooled results across multiple geographical units and the sensitivity analyses are done for pooled results for all units. I am including the sensitivity analysis with one ZCTA data here for simplicity.

Try different degree of freedom for long-term and seaonal trend

Here I tried to pick the appropriate degree of freedom by comparing the RR estimated using different df. Alternatively, we could choose a df based on previous knowledge or comparing Akaike Information Criterion of models with different df (extraction of AIC is not straightforward in quisi-Poisson model though). Please see Peng et al.2006 for more details on model choices.

nyr <- 8 # number of years from 2006 to 2013
df.tp <- 6 # number of degree of freedom for temperature terms
df.dp <- 3 # number of degree of freedom for dew point temperature terms

bar <- numeric()
for (ndf in c(1:20)) { ## use 1 to 20 degree of freedom per year
  f <- glm(cardio_disease ~ offset(log(pop)) + mean_pm25 + ns(day, df = nyr * ndf) + ns(tmpt, df.tp) + ns(dptp, df.dp) + ns(rmtmpt, df.tp) + ns(rmdptp, df.dp), data=dt, family = quasipoisson)
  foo <- data.frame(df = ndf,
                  beta = summary(f)$coefficients["mean_pm25", 1], 
                  se = summary(f)$coefficients["mean_pm25", 2], 
                  dispersion = summary(f)$dispersion)
  foo$est <- exp(foo$beta*10)
  foo$ll <- exp((foo$beta - 1.96 * foo$se)*10)
  foo$ul <- exp((foo$beta + 1.96 * foo$se)*10)
  bar <- rbind(bar, foo)
}
print(ggplot(bar, aes(y=est, x=df, ymax=ul, ymin=ll)) + 
          geom_hline(yintercept = 1, col="darkgrey", size=1.2) +
          geom_point(position=position_dodge(width=0.9), size=3) + 
        geom_errorbar(position=position_dodge(width=0.9), width=0.2, size=1.2) + 
          scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set2") + 
          labs(title="Sensitivity-df adjustment", x="Df per year considered in long-term and seaonal trend", 
               y=expression(atop("Rate ratio of hospital admissions",
                                 "per 10"~mu*"g/m"^3~"increase in PM"[2.5]))) + 
          theme(text = element_text(size=16), plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)))

Try different lag structures

I created \(PM_{2.5}\) with one day lag (mean_pm25l1) and moving average of \(PM_{2.5}\) in the same day and previous two days (mean_pm25m02). I also created distributed lag of \(PM_{2.5}\) (mean_pm25d06) considering lag effect for up to 7 days with two internal knots placed at corresponding quantiles (33% and 66%). I did not show the results here but running a quasi-Poisson model with these exposure metrics will produce corresponding effect estimates.

## create single day exposure with one day lag (previous day exposure)
dt[, mean_pm25l1 := shift(dt$mean_pm25, n = 1, fill = NA, type = "lag")]

## create moving average of current to previous two days (72 hours)
dt[, mean_pm25m02:= frollapply(dt$mean_pm25, n=3, FUN=mean, fill=NA, align="right")]

## below I created a distributed lag model
arglag <- list(fun="ns", range=0:6, int.knots=2) # specify variables for constrained distributed lag
cc <- ns(arglag$range, df=arglag$int.knots+1+1, intercept = TRUE)
temp.lag <- sapply(arglag$range, function(a) 
  shift(dt$mean_pm25, n = a, fill = NA, type = "lag")
  # tsModel::Lag(dt$mean_pm2, a) # this also works and is easy to add a by subgroup statement if needed
  )
mean_pm25d06 <- temp.lag %*% cc
dt <- cbind(dt, mean_pm25d06)
names(dt)[(ncol(dt)-3):ncol(dt)] <- paste("mean_pm25d06", 1:4, sep="_")
